oracle.apps.fnd.applcore.util
Class CdfsFriendlyNames

java.lang.Object
  oracle.apps.fnd.applcore.util.DistinctNames
      oracle.apps.fnd.applcore.util.CdfsFriendlyNames
Direct Known Subclasses:
ServiceFriendlyNames, SqlFriendlyNames
public class CdfsFriendlyNames
extends DistinctNames

Names that can be used as filenames as defined in ISO 9660, also referred to as CDFS (Compact Disc File System). Names formatted by this class will not contain dots, and their lengths will never exceed 255. A CDFS-friendly name can start with with a numeric digit.

Method Detail

name

public java.lang.String name(java.lang.String hint)
Creates a name according to the hint without adding the name to this collection. The name created will conform to the restrictions defined by this class. It is not guaranteed that distinct hints produce distinct names. For example, two overly long hints may become the same name after truncation. The names are distinct only when the hints are added through the add method, and the names are distinct only within this collection.

The hint is first americanized, then encodeUnfriendlyCharsOnly is called to encode the name. Finally the name is truncated if its length exceeds the maximum length.

Overrides:
name in class DistinctNames
Parameters:
hint - the hint
Returns:
the name derived from the hint

public static java.util.Map<java.lang.Character,java.lang.String> getAmericanizationMap()
Gets the mapping from characters to their americanized counterparts. For example, Ã© is mapped to 'e' by removing the accent. This map contains only entries where the americanized counterpart exists and is different from the character. The user must never assume the existence of a particular entry, but when constainsKey returns true, get never returns null.

isFriendly

public static boolean isFriendly(java.lang.String name)
Returns true if the name is considered friendly by this class. While a name returned by name method is always friendly, a friendly name may not be considered "friendly" by an instance of this class. For example, a name may not be contained by an instance of this class because it is too long, but this method still returns true because the name can be friendly after the length limit imposed by the instance is removed.

Parameters:
name - the name
Returns:
true if the name is considered friendly by this class
Throws:
java.lang.NullPointerException - if the name is null
